{
  "text": "Leachates from plant parts have a negative effect on plants grown in bioassays [CITATION_1] . [CITATION_2] demonstrated that aqueous Adenostoma fasciculatum leaf-and canopy extracts that contained phenolic acids [CITATION_3] suppressed germination and growth of herbs in chaparral. In Californian savannas, root leachates of Quercus douglasii seedlings, composed mainly of hydrophobic components, reduced the biomass of Bromus diandrus . Foliage exudates of several Australian mediterranean trees reduced seed germination of Avena fatua [CITATION_4] . Leaf exudates of Cistus ladanifer that contained phenolic compounds inhibited germination of the least abundant species in the community [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "86702819",
